Use ASP.NET Core's **`WebApplicationFactory<T>`** (from `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing`) to create an in-memory test server, then pass its `HttpClient` into the MCP SDK's transport.

### Key pieces

**1. Test project dependencies**

```xml
<PackageReference Include="Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing" Version="9.*" />
<PackageReference Include="ModelContextProtocol" Version="0.*" />
<PackageReference Include="xunit" Version="2.*" />
```

**2. Integration test**

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing;
using ModelContextProtocol.Client;
using ModelContextProtocol.Protocol.Transport;

public class McpIntegrationTests : IClassFixture<WebApplicationFactory<Program>>
{
    private readonly WebApplicationFactory<Program> _factory;

    public McpIntegrationTests(WebApplicationFactory<Program> factory)
        => _factory = factory;

    [Fact]
    public async Task CallTool_ReturnsExpectedResult()
    {
        // WebApplicationFactory gives you an HttpClient wired to the
        // in-memory test server — no real port, no real server process.
        var httpClient = _factory.CreateClient();

        // Point the MCP transport at the test server's base address.
        var transport = new SseClientTransport(
            new SseClientTransportOptions
            {
                Endpoint = new Uri(httpClient.BaseAddress!, "/sse"),
                Name = "test-client"
            },
            httpClient);   // ← inject the factory's HttpClient

        // For Streamable HTTP (newer servers), use instead:
        // var transport = new StreamableHttpClientTransport(
        //     new Uri(httpClient.BaseAddress!, "/mcp"),
        //     httpClient);

        await using var client = await McpClientFactory.CreateAsync(transport);

        var result = await client.CallToolAsync("my-tool", new { input = "hello" });

        Assert.NotNull(result);
        Assert.Contains("expected-value", result.Content[0].Text);
    }
}
```

### Why this works

| Concern | How it's handled |
|---|---|
| No real server | `WebApplicationFactory` hosts your app in-process with a test `HttpMessageHandler` |
| Full protocol fidelity | The MCP SDK client sends real MCP JSON-RPC over HTTP/SSE, same as production |
| Service overrides | Call `_factory.WithWebHostBuilder(b => b.ConfigureServices(...))` to swap dependencies |
| `Program` visibility | Add `<InternalsVisibleTo Include="YourTestProject" />` or a partial class if `Program` is implicit |

This gives you end-to-end MCP protocol coverage (initialize → list tools → call tool → shutdown) entirely in-process.
